---
import ShowcaseCard from '../../components/ShowcaseCard.astro';
import SpriteStrip from '../../components/SpriteStrip.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { monsterPages } from '../../data/showcase';
import type { FlatEntry } from '../../data/showcase';

const entryCount = monsterPages.reduce((total, page) => total + page.entries.length, 0);
const monsterEntries = monsterPages.flatMap((page) => page.entries);
const bestiaryRibbon = ['demon-3', 'ent-3', 'beholder-3']
  .map((slug) => monsterEntries.find((entry) => entry.slug === slug))
  .filter((entry): entry is FlatEntry => Boolean(entry))
  .slice(0, 3);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Monsters | Via Occulta"
  description="Via Occulta bestiary dossiers for undead, slimes, infernal forms, forest threats, constructs, and dungeon ecology."
>
  <section class="page-hero codex-hero-section">
    <div class="shell codex-hero">
      <div class="codex-hero__copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Bestiary codex</p>
        <h1>Threats from the roads that no longer stay where they belong.</h1>
        <p>
          Monsters are not random encounters pasted onto a map. They are evidence: undead remnants,
          infernal trespassers, alchemical spillover, forest hunger, and failed guardians showing where
          the Viae Occultae have broken.
        </p>
        <div class="pill-row">
          <span class="pill">{monsterPages.length} threat families</span>
          <span class="pill">{entryCount} logged sightings</span>
          <span class="pill">Route failure made visible</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="codex-slate codex-slate--threat panel" aria-label="Bestiary codex preview">
        <div class="codex-slate__header">
          <span>Threat register</span>
          <strong>Crypt / Forest / Underway</strong>
        </div>
        <SpriteStrip entries={bestiaryRibbon} scale={2} label="Monster family preview" density="hero" loading="eager" showLabels={false} />
        <div class="codex-slate__note">
          <p>Each sighting is framed by what it tells the player about a broken route, a failed rite, or a dungeon ecology pushing into town life.</p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell split">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Bestiary role</p>
        <h2>Monsters are evidence of infrastructure failure.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Monsters in Via Occulta do not simply invade from wilderness. Many appear from inside the road-network itself, wearing the shapes of old local spirits, failed guardians, hungry under-routes, and forgotten dead.
        </p>
        <p>
          The bestiary supports the game loop: Tenebrio reads or avoids them, Luciphilus fights them, and Opiphilus turns recovered proof into repairs, tools, recipes, and warnings.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">Dossiers</p>
      <h2>Bestiary files from unstable routes.</h2>
      <div class="showcase-list">
        {monsterPages.map((page) => <ShowcaseCard page={page} href={`monsters/${page.slug}`} />)}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
